    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-06-12T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-06-12T20:00:00-05:00" n="176"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d176">
                <head>176. Memorandum of a Conversation Between the <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                        State</gloss> and Chancellor <persName corresp="#p_AK1" type="to"
                        >Adenauer</persName>, Washington, June 12, 1956, 8 p.m.<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d176fn1">Source: Department of State, Secretary’s
                        Memoranda of Conversation: Lot 64 D 199. Secret. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_DAW1">Dulles</persName>. This conversation took place at
                        Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DAW1">Dulles</persName>’ house at dinner.
                            <persName corresp="#p_AK1">Adenauer</persName> was in Washington for a
                        series of discussions with U.S. officials over a 3-day period, June
                        12–14.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1956-06-12T20:00:00-05:00"
                            >June 12, 1956, 8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>At dinner we had some discussion about <gloss target="#t_EURATOM1"
                        >EURATOM</gloss> with the Chancellor and also with <persName
                        corresp="#p_HW1">Hallstein</persName>, who sat at my left, and to whom the
                    Chancellor referred some of my questions. <persName corresp="#p_AK1"
                        >Adenauer</persName> said that they were afraid that the <gloss
                        target="#t_EURATOM1">EURATOM</gloss> was being set up in such a way that it
                    would promote socialism. He favored the idea in principle, but did not want it
                    to operate to socialize industry in Europe. <persName corresp="#p_HW1"
                        >Hallstein</persName> said that on this account they had felt compelled to
                    make a reservation at the Venice meeting. He felt that the agency should not
                    retain ownership, but should exercise all the controls that could be exercised
                    if there were ownership.</p>
                <pb facs="0475" n="447" xml:id="pg_447"/>
                <p>I spoke of the relationship of <gloss target="#t_EURATOM1">EURATOM</gloss> to the
                    common market and said that while the United States favored both developments,
                    it did not seem to us wise to condition one upon the other. I felt that each
                    step could be taken on its own merits and that the creation of <gloss
                        target="#t_EURATOM1">EURATOM</gloss> would of itself maintain a momentum
                    favorable to the common market. <persName corresp="#p_HW1">Hallstein</persName>
                    seemed to indicate acceptance of this view, but somewhat confusedly.</p>
            </div>
